05490nam a22005535i 9780822391593DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20102009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223915937 a10.1515/97808223915932doi  a(DE-B1597)553455  a(OCoLC)1202623712  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aLC311b.D43 2009 7aEDU0150002bisacsh00aDebating Moral Education :bRethinking the Role of the Modern University /cJ. Peter Euben, Elizabeth Kiss. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (362 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1. DEBATING MORAL EDUCATION: AN INTRODUCTION -- t2. THE CHANGING CONTOURS OF MORAL EDUCATION IN AMERICAN COLLEGES AND UNIVERSITIES -- t3. AIM HIGH: A RESPONSE TO STANLEY FISH -- t4. I KNOW IT WHEN I SEE IT: A REPLY TO KISS AND EUBEN -- t5. THE PATHOS OF THE UNIVERSITY: THE CASE OF STANLEY FISH -- t6. ON THE DISTRIBUTION OF MORAL BADGES: A FEW WORRIES -- t7. PLURALISM AND THE EDUCATION OF THE SPIRIT -- t8. MULTICULTURALISM AND MORAL EDUCATION -- t9. AGAINST CIVIC EDUCATION IN SCHOOLS -- t10. EDUCATION, INDEPENDENCE, AND ACKNOWLEDGMENT -- t11. THE POWER OF MORALITY -- t12. HUNGER, ETHICS, AND THE UNIVERSITY: A RADICAL DEMOCRATIC GOAD IN TEN PIECES -- t13. IS THERE AN ETHICIST IN THE HOUSE? HOW CAN WE TELL? -- t14. THE POSSIBILITY OF MORAL EDUCATION IN THE UNIVERSITY TODAY -- t15. IS HUMANISTIC EDUCATION HUMANIZING? -- t16. PLAYERS AND SPECTATORS: SPORTS AND ETHICAL TRAINING IN THE AMERICAN UNIVERSITY -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter decades of marginalization in the secularized twentieth-century academy, moral education has enjoyed a recent resurgence in American higher education, with the establishment of more than 100 ethics centers and programs on campuses across the country. Yet the idea that the university has a civic responsibility to teach its undergraduate students ethics and morality has been met with skepticism, suspicion, and even outright rejection from both inside and outside the academy. In this collection, renowned scholars of philosophy, politics, and religion debate the role of ethics in the university, investigating whether universities should proactively cultivate morality and ethics, what teaching ethics entails, and what moral education should accomplish. The essays quickly open up to broader questions regarding the very purpose of a university education in modern society.Editors Elizabeth Kiss and J. Peter Euben survey the history of ethics in higher education, then engage with provocative recent writings by Stanley Fish in which he argues that universities should not be involved in moral education. Stanley Hauerwas responds, offering a theological perspective on the university's purpose. Contributors look at the place of politics in moral education; suggest that increasingly diverse, multicultural student bodies are resources for the teaching of ethics; and show how the debate over civic education in public grade-schools provides valuable lessons for higher education. Others reflect on the virtues and character traits that a moral education should foster in students-such as honesty, tolerance, and integrity-and the ways that ethical training formally and informally happens on campuses today, from the classroom to the basketball court. Debating Moral Education is a critical contribution to the ongoing discussion of the role and evolution of ethics education in the modern liberal arts university.Contributors. Lawrence Blum, Romand Coles, J. Peter Euben, Stanley Fish, Michael Allen Gillespie, Ruth W. Grant, Stanley Hauerwas, David A. Hoekema, Elizabeth Kiss, Patchen Markell, Susan Jane McWilliams, Wilson Carey McWilliams, J. Donald Moon, James Bernard Murphy, Noah Pickus, Julie A. Reuben, George Shulman, Elizabeth V. Spelman  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aMoral education (Higher)zUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh1 aEuben, J. Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKiss, Elizabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPickus, Noah1 aReuben, Julie A.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822391593zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822391593423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822391593.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles